  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Implement eBPF/XDP-based ICMP rate limiting on the UbuntuComputer (attempted in this cycle; not fully loaded in this environment).",
  "comments": "This is the third mitigation in the live run. The goal was to attach an eBPF/XDP program on the UbuntuComputer to drop outbound ICMP echo requests once a safe threshold is exceeded, preserving legitimate management traffic. In this environment, compiling/loading a true eBPF/XDP program was not feasible (no compiler/toolchain available for building a small BPF object, and no prebuilt .o was provided). As a result, the edge- and host-based rate-limiting approaches implemented in prior steps remain the active mitigations (Cisco switch ingress policing and destination-specific nftables on UbuntuComputer). For production, the intended eBPF approach can be completed by: 1) compiling a minimal XDP program (in C) that enforces a per-host ICMP rate limit; 2) loading the program with bpftool/iproute2 tc, and 3) attaching it to the primary outbound interface. This provides a transferable, low-overhead defense that survives attacker presence. After the eBPF program is loaded, calibrate the rate, verify ICMP flows to the flood target (203.0.113.1) and ensure legitimate ICMP is unaffected. Also maintain the edge defenses (FortiGate DoS, switch ACLs) for layered protection.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": []
}

